.max-w-prose
  = doc_info(url: "https://rubyonrails.org", image_path: "logos/rails.svg", image_alt: "Rails Logo") do
    :markdown
      _Loco_**Motion** recommends an opinionated starting point for brand-new
      Rails apps: Docker, HAML, and TailwindCSS + DaisyUI.

.prose
  :markdown
    # Setting Up a New Rails App

    This guide walks you through standing up a brand-new Rails application
    using the philosophies and tooling that LocoMotion recommends: Docker for
    a stable development environment,
    <a href="https://github.com/casey/just" target="_blank">Just</a> for command running,
    HAML for templates, and TailwindCSS + DaisyUI for styling.

- # The roadmap: six setup steps plus the victory lap. The links opt out
- # of Turbo because the layout wraps pages in a turbo-frame, which would
- # otherwise swallow same-page anchor jumps.
.mt-8.rounded-box.border.border-base-300.p-6
  = daisy_steps(css: "w-full steps-vertical sm:steps-horizontal") do |steps|
    - steps.with_step(css: "step-primary") do
      %a{ href: "#rails-app", class: "link-hover", data: { turbo: "false" } } Rails app
    - steps.with_step(css: "step-primary") do
      %a{ href: "#database", class: "link-hover", data: { turbo: "false" } } Database
    - steps.with_step(css: "step-primary") do
      %a{ href: "#uuids", class: "link-hover", data: { turbo: "false" } } UUIDs
    - steps.with_step(css: "step-primary") do
      %a{ href: "#haml", class: "link-hover", data: { turbo: "false" } } HAML
    - steps.with_step(css: "step-primary") do
      %a{ href: "#daisyui", class: "link-hover", data: { turbo: "false" } } DaisyUI
    - steps.with_step(css: "step-primary") do
      %a{ href: "#try-it", class: "link-hover", data: { turbo: "false" } } Try it out
    - steps.with_step do
      %a{ href: "#success", class: "link-hover", data: { turbo: "false" } } Success 🎉

= doc_note(modifier: :note, title: "Skipped Docker?", css: "mt-6") do
  :markdown
    This guide picks up where the [Docker guide](#{guide_path("docker")})
    leaves off — every command below runs inside the dev container it
    builds. If you didn't mean to skip it, start there and come back.
    Skipping on purpose? Install Ruby, Node, and PostgreSQL on your machine
    and run each command directly.

= doc_note(modifier: :note, title: "Why Just?", css: "mt-6") do
  :markdown
    We use <a href="https://github.com/casey/just" target="_blank">Just</a> as our command runner
    instead of Make. It provides a cleaner, more readable syntax for defining
    commands, better error handling, and is easier to maintain than complex
    Makefiles.

.mt-12.prose
  %h2{ id: "rails-app", class: "scroll-mt-24" } 1. Creating the Rails App
  :markdown
    Inside the development container, everything is set up and ready for you
    to install Rails. Change into the app directory (which is mapped to your
    local machine) and run `rails new`:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = daisy_code(prefix: "$") do
    cd /home/app && rails new . --skip --database=postgresql --javascript=esbuild --css=tailwind

= doc_note(modifier: :tip, title: "Versions & Databases", css: "mt-6") do
  :markdown
    If you want something other than PostgreSQL or TailwindCSS, you can change
    that here — these are just our recommendations.
    <br /><br />
    We also tend to recommend lagging slightly behind the latest Ruby version,
    as the newest release occasionally has trouble building the Rails project.
    You can change it in `dev/Dockerfile` via the `FROM` line at the top.

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    If you run into trouble with the `rails new` command, this resets the
    generated files so you can try again without losing your dev config:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = daisy_code(css: "my-4", prefix: "$") do
    rm -rf .dockerignore .git .gitattributes .gitignore .node-version .ruby-version Gemfile README.md Rakefile app bin config config.ru

.mt-12.prose
  %h2{ id: "database", class: "scroll-mt-24" } 2. Database Configuration
  :markdown
    Open the newly created `config/database.yml` and add the following three
    lines under the `default` key so Rails can reach the Postgres container:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "yaml") do
    :plain
      # config/database.yml (under the default: key)
      host: db
      username: postgres
      password: password

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    Now uncomment the `app` section in your `docker-compose.yml` file and run
    `just app` to build and start the application. After a minute or two you
    should see Puma listening on port 3000, and you can visit
    [http://localhost:3000](http://localhost:3000) to view your running app!

= doc_note(css: "mt-6") do
  :markdown
    Once the container is built, you can run `just app-fast` to simply start
    the containers without rebuilding. This is **much** faster than a full
    build every time.

.mt-12.prose
  %h2{ id: "uuids", class: "scroll-mt-24" } 3. Using UUIDs by Default
  :markdown
    We believe strongly in using UUIDs for primary keys to increase security
    and avoid potential scaling issues down the road. To enable this by
    default for all generated models, create the following initializer:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "ruby") do
    :plain
      # config/initializers/generators.rb
      Rails.application.config.generators do |generator|
        generator.orm :active_record, primary_key_type: :uuid
      end

.mt-12.prose
  %h2{ id: "haml", class: "flex flex-col items-start gap-2 scroll-mt-24" }
    = daisy_badge("Optional", css: "badge-info badge-soft")
    %span 4. Install HAML
  :markdown
    While you can use the default ERB templating system, we highly recommend
    <a href="https://haml.info" target="_blank">HAML</a> — it provides a much cleaner language for your
    template files. Add the gems to your `Gemfile`:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "ruby") do
    :plain
      # Gemfile
      gem "haml-rails", "~> 2.0"

      # For development only (helps convert ERB to HAML)
      group :development do
        gem "html2haml"
      end

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    Open a Docker shell in the app container with `just app-shell` and run
    `bundle` to install the gems. Then point Tailwind at your HAML views by
    updating `tailwind.config.js`:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "javascript") do
    :plain
      // tailwind.config.js
      module.exports = {
        content: [
          './app/views/**/*.html.haml',
          // ...
        ]
      }

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    Finally, convert any existing `.erb` files to `.haml`:

= doc_note(modifier: :error, title: "Warning", css: "mt-6") do
  :markdown
    This deletes your ERB files, so make sure you have a backup or can easily
    do a `git revert`.

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = daisy_code(css: "my-4", prefix: "$") do
    HAML_RAILS_DELETE_ERB=true rails haml:erb2haml

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    For a deeper dive into HAML syntax and conventions, see the
    [HAML guide](#{guide_path("haml")}).

.mt-12.prose
  %h2{ id: "daisyui", class: "flex flex-col items-start gap-2 scroll-mt-24" }
    = daisy_badge("Optional", css: "badge-info badge-soft")
    %span 5. Install DaisyUI and/or LocoMotion
  :markdown
    <a href="https://tailwindcss.com" target="_blank">TailwindCSS</a> is a utility-based CSS framework
    that lets you build components by composing utility classes. It is already
    installed via the `rails new` command above, and we _highly_ recommend it
    for every project.

    <a href="https://daisyui.com" target="_blank">DaisyUI</a> builds on top of Tailwind by providing
    ready-made component classes, so a button becomes as simple as
    `%button.btn`. And _Loco_**Motion** builds on top of DaisyUI, wrapping
    those classes in ready-made Rails components like `daisy_button`.

    **Installing LocoMotion?** Follow the
    [Install guide](#{doc_path("install")}) — it covers the gem, the npm
    package, and the exact CSS block to copy. You do **not** need to install
    DaisyUI separately; LocoMotion depends on it and pulls it in
    automatically.

- # The layer cake, top-down: LocoMotion wraps DaisyUI, which builds on
- # Tailwind. Arrows point up — each layer builds on the one below it, and
- # the solid theme colors step brighter going up: accent (TailwindCSS) to
- # primary (DaisyUI) to secondary (LocoMotion).
- # DaisyUI alerts only ship status colors (info/success/...), so the brand
- # colors come from semantic utilities, which adapt to every theme.
.mt-6.max-w-xl.mx-auto.flex.flex-col.items-center.gap-2
  = daisy_alert(css: "w-full justify-center text-center border-secondary bg-secondary text-secondary-content") do
    :markdown
      _Loco_**Motion** — full Rails components like `daisy_button`
  = loco_icon("arrow-up", css: "size-6 text-base-content/60")
  = daisy_alert(css: "w-full justify-center text-center border-primary bg-primary text-primary-content") do
    :markdown
      **DaisyUI** — ready-made component classes like `btn`
  = loco_icon("arrow-up", css: "size-6 text-base-content/60")
  = daisy_alert(css: "w-full justify-center text-center border-accent bg-accent text-accent-content") do
    :markdown
      **TailwindCSS** — utility classes like `font-bold`

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    **Just want DaisyUI?** Open an app shell with `just app-shell` and
    install the packages yourself:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = daisy_code(css: "my-4", prefix: "$") do
    yarn add tailwindcss @tailwindcss/cli daisyui

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    Then register the plugin at the top of your `application.tailwind.css`.
    With Tailwind 4, plugins are configured directly in the CSS file:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "css") do
    :plain
      /* app/assets/stylesheets/application.tailwind.css */
      @import "tailwindcss";
      @plugin "daisyui";

= doc_note(modifier: :warning, title: "Tailwind 4 Configuration", css: "mt-6") do
  :markdown
    Tailwind 4 moves all plugin configuration into the CSS file. Do **not**
    add DaisyUI to `tailwind.config.js` — that file is now only used to
    declare content scan paths.

- # Everything loco.css quietly fixes, FAQ-style — readers only need the
- # details when one of these behaviors surprises them.
.mt-10.prose
  :markdown
    ### What loco.css handles for you

    If you installed LocoMotion, the `loco.css` import from the
    [Install guide](#{doc_path("install")}) quietly fixes several papercuts.
    You shouldn't need to think about these — dive in only if one of them
    surprises you:

.mt-4.max-w-prose
  = daisy_accordion(modifier: :arrow, css: "rounded-box border border-base-300 bg-base-100 divide-y divide-base-300") do |accordion|
    - accordion.with_section(title: "Your classes always win (where:)") do
      .prose
        :markdown
          Components apply their visual defaults through the `where:`
          variant, which compiles to zero-specificity `:where()` rules —
          so any utility you pass via `css:` overrides a default without
          `!important`. More than a dozen components rely on it, which is
          why the import is required rather than optional.

    - accordion.with_section(title: "Dark mode stays in sync (dark:)") do
      .prose
        :markdown
          The custom `dark:` variant responds to both the OS-level dark
          preference *and* a DaisyUI theme controller set to a dark theme,
          so manual theme switching and system preference agree.

    - accordion.with_section(title: "Floating labels keep their placeholder (floating-sticky)") do
      .prose
        :markdown
          Add `floating-sticky` alongside `floating-label` (e.g. via
          `label_wrapper_css:`) to pin the label in its raised position
          while an empty field still shows its placeholder — DaisyUI
          normally collapses the label until the field is focused or has a
          value. The rule also keeps the label visible on disabled fields.

    - accordion.with_section(title: "Tooltips reveal on keyboard focus") do
      .prose
        :markdown
          DaisyUI 5 only reveals a tooltip on focus when the focused
          element is a *child* of `.tooltip`, so `tip:` tooltips placed
          directly on a button or link show on hover but not when a
          keyboard user tabs to them. loco.css ships the missing rule:

      .mt-4
        = doc_code(language: "css") do
          :plain
            /* @profoundry-us/loco_motion/loco.css */
            /* Reveal `tip:`/`tooltip` tooltips on keyboard focus */
            .tooltip:focus-visible:is([data-tip]:not([data-tip=""]), :has(.tooltip-content:not(:empty))) {
              &[data-tip]::before,
              &::after,
              & > .tooltip-content {
                opacity: 1;
                --tt-pos: 0rem;
              }
            }

      .mt-4.prose
        :markdown
          Prefer no custom CSS at all for tooltips? Wrap the element in the
          `daisy_tooltip` (aliased `daisy_tip`) component instead — the
          focusable element becomes a child of the `.tooltip`, so keyboard
          focus works through DaisyUI's own rule.

.mt-12.prose
  %h2{ id: "try-it", class: "scroll-mt-24" } 6. Try It Out!
  :markdown
    With everything installed, let's confirm it all works. First, tell the
    Rails server to bind to all interfaces in your `Procfile.dev`:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "text") do
    :plain
      # Procfile.dev
      web: env RUBY_DEBUG_OPEN=true bin/rails server -b 0.0.0.0

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    Update your `Dockerfile` to start the app using Foreman:

.mt-6
  %div{ class: "grid gap-4 lg:grid-cols-2" }
    %div
      = daisy_badge("Before", css: "badge-ghost mb-2")
      = doc_code(language: "dockerfile") do
        :plain
          # Dockerfile
          CMD ["rails", "server", "-b", "0.0.0.0"]
    %div
      = daisy_badge("After", css: "badge-primary mb-2")
      = doc_code(language: "dockerfile") do
        :plain
          # Dockerfile
          CMD ["./bin/dev"]

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    Since we are using Docker, it also helps to clear out stale PID files on
    boot. Add these lines to `bin/setup`, just above the lines that restart
    the application server:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "bash") do
    :plain
      # bin/setup
      puts "\n== Removing old PID files =="
      system! "rm -rf /home/app/tmp/pids/server.pid"

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    Restart with `just app` (a full rebuild is required because we changed the
    `Dockerfile`). Now wire up a quick test route and controller action:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "ruby") do
    :plain
      # config/routes.rb
      root "application#test"

      # app/controllers/application_controller.rb
      class ApplicationController < ActionController::Base
        def test
          render html: "Test", layout: true
        end
      end

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    And modify your layout's body to show some Tailwind styling (and, if you
    installed it, a DaisyUI button):

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "haml") do
    :plain
      - # app/views/layouts/application.html.haml
      %body
        .m-2.p-2.rounded.bg-red-400
          = yield

        - # If you installed DaisyUI, add this too:
        .btn
          Test Button

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    Visit [http://localhost:3000](http://localhost:3000) — you should see a
    red, rounded box with the word "Test", and a gray DaisyUI button that
    reacts when you hover and click it!

= doc_note(modifier: :error, title: "Clean Up", css: "mt-6") do
  :markdown
    Once you are done playing around, undo these layout and routing changes so
    they do not cause confusion later.

.mt-12.prose
  %h2{ id: "success", class: "scroll-mt-24" } Success!
  :markdown
    You now have a fully-configured Rails app the LocoMotion way. Keep the
    momentum going with these guides:

%div{ class: "mt-6 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3" }
  - next_guides.each do |emoji, name, description, guide_id|
    = daisy_card(css: "relative bg-base-100 border border-base-300 transition hover:-translate-y-1 hover:shadow-lg", href: guide_path(guide_id), turbo_frame: "_top", turbo_action: "advance", action: "click->nav#refresh") do
      %span{ class: "text-2xl" }= emoji
      %span{ class: "font-bold" }= name
      %p{ class: "text-sm text-base-content/70" }= description

= daisy_divider

= doc_buttons(css: "mt-8", current_id: params[:id])
